In your Ionic/Angular app, you need to ensure the headers match exactly what your Flask server expects. In your PostsComponent, you're missing the closing brace for the headers object. Here's the corrected version:

typescript
ngOnInit() {
  const lang = localStorage.getItem('lang') || 'sk';
  const headers = new HttpHeaders({
    'Accept-Language': lang
  });

  this.http.get('http://miki83.pythonanywhere.com/', {
    headers: headers
  }).subscribe(data => {
    console.log(data);  // Make sure to log the actual response
    this.posts = data;
  });
}


The server expects an 'Accept-Language' header with a language code (like 'sk', 'en', etc.), which your code correctly implements.

First, verify the request is reaching your server by checking PythonAnywhere's access logs. Then in your Ionic app, add proper error handling:

typescript
this.http.get('http://miki83.pythonanywhere.com/', { headers })
  .subscribe({
    next: (data) => {
      console.log('Success:', data);
      this.posts = data;
    },
    error: (err) => {
      console.error('Error:', err.status, err.message, err.url);
      if (err.status === 0) {
        console.log('Check network connectivity or CORS settings');
      }
    }
  });


Also test the API endpoint directly using curl or Postman to isolate whether the issue is with the server or client.

The main issues are:

1. **Missing error handling** - The subscription doesn't handle potential errors
2. **Debugging limitations** - The empty console.log() doesn't help diagnose issues
3. **Potential subscription leak** - No cleanup mechanism if the component is destroyed

Here's an improved version:

typescript
ngOnInit() {
  const lang = localStorage.getItem('lang') || 'sk';
  const headers = new HttpHeaders({'Accept-Language': lang});

  this.http.get('http://miki83.pythonanywhere.com/', { headers })
    .subscribe({
      next: (data) => {
        console.log('Received data:', data);
        this.posts = data;
      },
      error: (err) => {
        console.error('Failed to load posts:', err);
        // Consider adding user feedback here
      }
    });
}

ngOnDestroy() {
  // Clean up to prevent memory leaks
}


Also verify that your Angular HttpClient is properly imported and configured in your app module.
